\(Q\\subset\\mathbb{R}^n\\),\n\\[\n\\left|\\int_Q \\varphi(x)\\,dx\\right| \\le \\frac{M\\, m(Q)}{1+m(Q)},\n\\]\nwhere \\(m(Q)\\) is the Lebesgue measure of \\(Q\\) and \\(M\\) is a fixed constant. The bound forces the average value over big boxes to decay like \\(1/m(Q)\\). We must prove that for every \\(f\\in L^1(\\mathbb{R}^n)\\), the oscillatory integrals against dilates of \\(\\varphi\\) vanish:\n\\[\n\\lim_{k\\to\\infty} \\int_{\\mathbb{R}^n} \\varphi(kx) f(x)\\,dx = 0.\n\\]\nInformally: the “large-scale averaged” part of \\(\\varphi\\) becomes negligible when tested against any \\(L^1\\) function.\n\n**WHY IT IS HARD**  \nThe condition on \\(\\varphi\\) involves averages over rectangles, not pointwise bounds, so standard dominated-convergence or Riemann–Lebesgue arguments don’t apply directly. The challenge is to exploit the decay of large-rectangle averages to control the integrals of \\(\\varphi(kx)\\) against arbitrary \\(L^1\\) functions. Students often try to use Fourier analysis or naive scaling, but the hypothesis is purely spatial, with no decay at infinity or integrability. The real tool is an approximation-by-step-functions or differentiation-of-integrals argument: approximate \\(f\\) by simple functions supported on rectangles, use the rectangle bound to kill each piece after a change of variables, and then pass to the limit. Recognizing that the integral condition controls \\(\\varphi\\) when averaged at large scales—and coupling that with density of simple functions in \\(L^1\\)—is the prerequisite being tested.", :propose "**THE KEY INSIGHT**  \nApproximate \\(f\\) by simple functions supported on rectangles, then use the scaling change-of-variables to reduce \\(\\int \\varphi(kx) f(x)\\,dx\\) to sums of rectangle integrals of \\(\\varphi\\). Specifically, for a simple function \\(f=\\sum_j a_j \\mathbf{1}_{Q_j}\\),\n\\[\n\\int_{\\mathbb{R}^n} \\varphi(kx) f(x)\\,dx\n= \\sum_j a_j \\int_{Q_j} \\varphi(kx)\\,dx\n= \\sum_j a_j k^{-n} \\int_{k Q_j} \\varphi(u)\\,du.\n\\]\nThe hypothesis bounds each rectangle integral by \\(M m(kQ_j)/(1+m(kQ_j))\\), which tends to zero as \\(k\\to\\infty\\) because \\(m(kQ_j)=k^n m(Q_j)\\). Hence the integral against each simple function vanishes in the limit. Since simple functions are dense in \\(L^1\\), the result follows for all \\(f\\). The key is that the average of \\(\\varphi\\) over larger and larger rectangles tends to zero, so dilating the rectangles in the change of variables wipes out the contribution.\n\n**THE NAIVE APPROACH THAT FAILS**  \nA common first attempt is to treat \\(\\varphi\\) as if it had decay or belonged to \\(L^1\\), trying dominated convergence or the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma. However, the hypothesis gives no pointwise control or integrability of \\(\\varphi\\); it only bounds integrals over rectangles in terms of volume. Without approximating \\(f\\) by rectangular indicators, one cannot exploit the given condition. Another misstep is to try to prove that \\(\\varphi(kx)\\to0\\) pointwise, which is not implied by the rectangle averages. The structural obstruction is that we control only averages over boxes, so we must decompose \\(f\\) into such boxes (simple functions) and use the change-of-variables argument—any approach that ignores this averaging structure fails.", :execute "Stage 1 — THE CLEAN PROOF\n--------------------------------\n\nTake \\(f\\in L^1(\\mathbb{R}^n)\\). For any \\(\\varepsilon>0\\), pick a simple function \\(g=\\sum_{j=1}^m a_j\\mathbf{1}_{Q_j}\\) (with axis-aligned rectangles \\(Q_j\\)) such that \\(\\|f-g\\|_{L^1}<\\varepsilon/M\\). For fixed \\(k>0\\),\n\\[\n\\int_{\\mathbb{R}^n}\\varphi(kx)g(x)\\,dx\n=\\sum_{j=1}^m a_j k^{-n}\\int_{kQ_j}\\varphi(u)\\,du,\n\\]\nand the hypothesis implies\n\\[\n\\left|\\int_{kQ_j}\\varphi(u)\\,du\\right|\n\\le \\frac{M m(kQ_j)}{1+m(kQ_j)}\n= \\frac{M k^n m(Q_j)}{1+k^n m(Q_j)}\n\\le \\frac{M}{k^n} m(Q_j).\n\\]\nThus\n\\[\n\\left|\\int\\varphi(kx)g(x)\\,dx\\right|\n\\le \\frac{M}{k^n}\\su